SIMPLE: sour
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sour
<hw>Sour</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Sourer</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Sourest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sour</ets>,
<ets>sur</ets>, AS. <ets>s<?/r</ets>; akin to D. <ets>zuur</ets>, G.
<ets>sauer</ets>, OHG. <ets>s<?/r</ets>, Icel. <ets>s<?/rr</ets>, Sw.
<ets>sur</ets>, Dan. <ets>suur</ets>, Lith. <ets>suras</ets> salt, Russ.
<ets>surovui</ets> harsh, rough. Cf. <er>Sorrel</er>, the plant.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Having an acid or sharp, biting taste, like vinegar,
and the juices of most unripe fruits; acid; tart.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All <qex>sour</qex> things, as vinegar, provoke appetite.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Changed, as by keeping, so as to be acid, rancid, or
musty, turned.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Disagreeable; unpleasant; hence; cross; crabbed;
peevish; morose; <as>as, a man of a <ex>sour</ex> temper; a
<ex>sour</ex> reply.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>sour</xex>
countenance.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was a scholar . . . ⟦br⟧
Lofty and <qex>sour</qex> to them that loved him not,⟦br⟧
But to those men that sought him sweet as summer.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Afflictive; painful.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Sour</xex>
adversity.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Cold and unproductive; <as>as, <ex>sour</ex> land; a
<ex>sour</ex> marsh.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sour dock</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>sorrel.</cd>
-- <col><b>Sour gourd</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the gourdlike
fruit <spn>Adansonia Gregorii</spn>, and <spn>Adansonia digitata</spn>;
also, either of the trees bearing this fruit. See
<er>Adansonia</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sour grapes</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Grape</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sour gum</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>
<cd>See <er>Turelo</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sour plum</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the edible acid fruit of an Australian tree
(<spn>Owenia venosa</spn>); also, the tree itself, which furnished a
hard reddish wood used by wheelwrights.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Acid; sharp; tart; acetous; acetose; harsh;
acrimonious; crabbed; currish; peevish.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sour</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sour
<hw>Sour</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sour or acid substance; whatever
produces a painful effect.</def> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sour</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sour
<hw>Sour</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>s<?/rian</ets> to sour,
to become sour.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to become sour; to
cause to turn from sweet to sour; <as>as, exposure to the air
<ex>sours</ex> many substances</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So the sun's heat, with different powers,⟦br⟧
Ripens the grape, the liquor <qex>sours</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make cold and unproductive, as soil.</def>
<rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make unhappy, uneasy, or less
agreeable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>sour</qex> your happiness I must report,⟦br⟧
The queen is dead.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cause or permit to become harsh or
unkindly.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Souring</xex> his cheeks.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pride had not <qex>sour'd</qex> nor wrath debased my heart.</q>
<rj><qau>Harte.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To macerate, and render fit for plaster or mortar;
<as>as, to <ex>sour</ex> lime for business purposes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sour</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sour
<hw>Sour</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Soured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Souring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To become sour; to turn from
sweet to sour; <as>as, milk soon <ex>sours</ex> in hot weather; a kind
temper sometimes <ex>sours</ex> in adversity.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They keep out melancholy from the virtuous, and hinder the hatred
of vice from <qex>souring</qex> into severity.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Source</ent>⟦br⟧
